  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Willow Catkins
  author: Lee Jae-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Like flowers yet not snow, how wildly they dance—
    Across the empty expanse, the gentle wind sends them astray.
    On clear days they scatter through the deep garden courts,
    Floating on the still waters of the small pond.
    When they alight on the stone steps, they cast no shadow,
    Blown through the silk screens, they bring their fragrant breath.
    Suddenly I recall those days at the eastern meadow,
    Reading among the falling blossoms that drifted across my empty bed.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Willow catkins (양화) are the downy seeds of the willow tree, often confused with snow or blossoms due to their appearance and movement through the air.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'eastern meadow' (동고) refers to a place of scholarly retreat and study, evoking the poet's youthful days of reading and contemplation.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'falling blossoms' (낙화) reference peach or plum blossoms, which in Chinese poetry traditionally symbolize the transience of beauty and youth.
